Munising Public Schools will be streaming all of our home athletic contests this school year. Many U.P. schools are adding streaming capabilities this fall as well. You can purchase an affordable streaming package at the link below. A monthly pass is $10.99 or an annual pass is $69.99. Go to the NFHS website, go to “Find your school” at the top, and type in Munising High School. You can hit the subscribe button and that will allow you to view the games that will available. Munising will be streaming all middle school, junior varsity and varsity contests. With indoor sports limited to 250 spectators and outdoor sports limited to 500, streaming may be a great option for some.

https://www.nfhsnetwork.com/subscribe/retail

For students that will be attending school virtually this fall through the Mustang Online program, if you are in need of a device, please stop by Mather Elementary or the Munising Middle/High School beginning Wednesday, September 9, 2020 to pick up a Chromebook.

Our online students will not begin instruction until the week of September 14, 2020, due to the high volume of schools and students utilizing GenNET Virtual for their online learning platform. Students will still complete their marking periods and semesters at the same time as students choosing in-person instruction. We will keep everyone updated with our most current information.

Thank you for your patience!

Great news!

All Munising Public Schools students will receive FREE meals! The United State Department of Agriculture (USDA) announced this week that they are extending the federal waiver that will provide FREE breakfast and lunch to ALL students through December 31, 2020 or until funding runs out. It is important to still fill out the free and reduced lunch applications due to the the waiver ending at some point.

Students will have to pay if they want more than one breakfast or lunch.

post_text:
Robotic Coding Camp SPIN Club Kicks off this month!

Register with MSU Extension 4-H at https://events.anr.msu.edu/roboticscodecamp2020/

Designed with middle schoolers in mind, this Robotics Coding Camp SPIN Club will meet daily August 17-20 at 3 p.m. EST on a Zoom meeting. Camp participants will engage in multiple computer programing activities, "plugged" and "unplugged" to learn about basic coding languages of Computer Science. Youth will gain an introductory understanding of Blocky programming language used by the FIRST Tech Challenge robots. Youth will need a desktop computer, laptop, or Chromebook to fully engage in this club. If you need a computer contact Carol Horne (hornecar@msu.edu) or Liz Wiener (wienerel@msu.edu) to make arrangements.

SUMMER LUNCH PROGRAM CHANGES

The Munising Public Schools lunch program will continue this summer with the following changes:

Free breakfast/lunch will be available for pick up and will be delivered to the existing pick up locations only through Friday, June 19. There will be no breakfast/lunch delivery or pick up from the Middle/High School from June 22 through June 30.

Effective Wednesday, July 1, free lunch pick up will be available again at the Middle/High School, and will continue on Monday, Wednesday and Friday each week through Friday, August 21. There will be no delivery to the existing pick up locations after June 19.

post_text:
BOARD OF EDUCATION VACANCY

Munising Public Schools Board of Education is seeking applications for a current vacant position on the board of education. An individual will be appointed to fill the vacant position through December 31, 2020 and will be replaced by the individual elected to the position (based on the November 2020 election results) on January 1, 2021. Persons interested in serving as a member of the Board must submit a letter of interest by Wednesday, June 24th stating the reasons they wish to be considered for the appointment.

Please mail or hand deliver the letter of interest to:

Munising Public Schools Board of Education
Attn: Jason Brisson, Vice President
Munising Middle/High School
810 State Highway M-28 West, Suite B
Munising, MI 49862

JV and Varsity Football conditioning (and middle school players if interested) begins on Monday, June 15 at 6:00pm at the Middle/High School. Players should meet in the parking lot so that appropriate distances can be kept and health monitoring forms can be filled out.

Prior to each workout or open gym, coaches will complete the attached form and take the temperature of each student-athlete. Any athlete answering yes to any of the questions or with a temperature above 100.3 degrees will be sent home.

post_text:
The Munising Middle/High School gymnasium floor resurfacing project is complete! The floor was last resurfaced in 1995, the only other time it had been resurfaced since the school opened in 1980.

The resurfacing was funded with some remaining bond proceeds from the school millage passed by district voters in November of 2017. Because the overall school renovation came in under budget, we are still able to complete some final projects. Thank you to the community again for supporting the millage.

Also, thank you to Foster Specialty Floors out of Wixom, Michigan for their professionalism and timeliness in completing the project.

#MunisingProud
#MustangProud
#SchoolSpirit

post_text: We are working hard to get your art work back to you (there is a lot of it)! The sixth grade art work and the 11th grade art work will be available for pick up at the Middle/High School starting Tuesday, June 9th between the hours of 8:00am-3:00pm. One parent and child may enter the building to pick up your art work. Please make sure you are wearing a mask. The art work is just inside the front door in front of the office on tables. Please look through your art work to make sure it is all yours before you leave. Mrs. Essinger will be here to help out but will not be delivering it to your car. We will limit the amount of people into the building at one time so please be patient if you are asked to wait.

post_text:
Munising Public Schools has set Saturday, June 13 at noon as the graduation date and time to honor the Munising High School Class of 2020!

Depending on what is allowed under the Governor's MI Safe Start Plan, the first option is to do the ceremony at Mustang Stadium with appropriate safety precautions and social distancing, but if that is not allowed due to the continued large gathering restrictions, the ceremony will be conducted as a "drive-in" ceremony in the high school parking lot, where people would stay in their cars. We will follow up either ceremony with a parade through town, so community members can honor the seniors as well.

If weather prohibits the outdoor graduation from being conducted on Saturday, June 13, then Sunday, June 14 at 1:00pm would the back-up date and time.

#MunisingClassOf2020

#MustangProud

In recognition of the Munising High School Class of 2020, we will be honoring two of our seniors each day on our Facebook page. We hope to still have a graduation ceremony once Governor Whitmer's "MI Safe Start Plan" further clarifies guidance on large gatherings.

Christopher Shelly is the son of Ron and Alethea Shelly. During his high school career, he was involved in football along with many other after school activities. Christopher was a member of the Robotics club, Munising Cyberstangs, Boy Scouts, Order of the Arrow, and the Michigan National Guard. His future plans are to pursue training with the Michigan National Guard as a Petroleum Specialist which involves fuel transportation and hazardous material transportation.

Best of luck Christopher!

#MunisingClassOf2020

In recognition of the Munising High School Class of 2020, we will be honoring two of our seniors each day on our Facebook page. We hope to still have a graduation ceremony once Governor Whitmer's "MI Safe Start Plan" further clarifies guidance on large gatherings.

Caylee Dusseault is the daughter of Jason and Laura Dusseault. Caylee has been involved in sideline and competitive cheer from 6th grade through her senior year. She was on competitive cheer teams that won back to back District Championships, were runners up at Regionals and competed at State Finals twice. Her team also won U.P. Team of the year in 2019 and 2020. Caylee participated in Key Club, Yearbook Committee, and the Peer to Peer Program her senior year and she is a member of the National Honor Society. Caylee participated in the Advanced Child Development class at Mather Elementary School with the 2nd and 5th grade students. She has been on the Honor Roll every year of high school. Caylee plans to pursue a Degree in Veterinary Science at Northern Michigan University.

Best of luck Caylee!

#MunisingClassOf2020

Cody Dowd is the son of Renee Dowd and the late Patrick Dowd. While in high school Cody participated in basketball. He also loved to compete and found many ways to do this with his fellow classmates. Cody’s plans are to take a break from furthering his education and enjoy his soon-to-be new role as an uncle while he decides on a course of study and which college he would like to attend.

Best of luck Cody!

#MunisingClassOf2020

In recognition of the Munising High School Class of 2020, we will be honoring two of our seniors each day on our Facebook page. We hope to still have a graduation ceremony once Governor Whitmer's "MI Safe Start Plan" further clarifies guidance on large gatherings.

Gabriel Cole is the son of Richard and Mandy Cole. He was a member of the football, wrestling, and track and field teams. He served as a captain in football and wrestling and was District Wrestling Champion his senior year. Gabe was inducted into the National Honor Society in his junior year, is a 4-year Honor Roll student, and is on the Upper Peninsula Wrestling Coaches Association All-Academic Team. He is a two-year Key Club member and volunteered as a youth wrestling referee. Gabriel will spend his second summer working at Superior Pontoon Rentals before attending Central Michigan University in the fall.

Best of luck Gabe!

#MunisingClassOf2020

post_text:
Munising Families,

Effective Monday, May 18th, Munising Public Schools is adjusting delivery times to our breakfast/lunch pick up locations. We will now have two vans transporting food on the following schedule:

Van 1
11:00 - 11:10am - Mather Elementary - Jewell Street Entrance
11:15 - 11:25am - Hillside Apartments - parking lot
11:30 - 11:40am - Christmas - West end of Kewadin Casino parking lot
11:50 - Noon - Autrain - Peoples State Bank parking lot

Van 2
11:00 - 11:10am - Wetmore - Baptist Church parking lot
11:20 - 11:30am - Shingleton - Munising Motor Sports parking lot
11:40 - 11:50am - Van Meer - Bear Trap parking lot
Noon - 12:10pm - Windjammer Apartments - parking lot

Deliveries will remain on Monday, Wednesday and Friday. Times are approximate.

Stay safe and healthy!

During Makayla’s high school career, she played on the tennis and golf teams for three years as well as the JV volleyball team for one year. Makayla’s future plans include attending Northern Michigan University to pursue a photography degree.

Best of luck Makayla!

Congratulations to former Munising High School students Jonn Hermann, James Eiseman and Bailey Masters on their graduation from NMU's Marquette-Alger Technical Middle College! A "virtual" graduation ceremony was conducted on Monday, May 11th.

The Middle College is a tuition-free early college program that enables students from Marquette and Alger Counties to earn a high school diploma and up to 44 college credits toward an NMU associate degree or a technical certificate at no cost to students or their families. It also provides a gradual, structured and supported transition from high school to college, resulting in greater college success and more residents with high-quality degrees and credentials.

#MustangProud

Welcome Munising Public Schools Graduating Class of 2033!

Even though Kindergarten Registration for the Munising Public Schools 2020-21 school year has been postponed, if you have a child that is 5 years old on or before September 01, 2020, please call 387-2102, extension 1132. We will add your child’s name to the roster for registration.

Please note, if your child is currently 4 years old, but their birthday falls between September 1, 2020 and December 1, 2020 you may request an age waiver to enroll them in kindergarten.

A registration date will be set when we have additional guidance from the Governor's Office.

Today is "School Lunch Hero Day" and we would like to honor our awesome heroes who have all contributed to feeding students during the school closure!

As of today, over 8,500 free breakfasts and lunches have been picked up or delivered since the closure went into effect on March 16!

Our School Lunch Heroes: Food service staff Laprel Morrison, Kelly Maki and Brenda Ekberg prepare and get the breakfasts and lunches ready to go; Bus drivers Kelly King, Loren King, Rick Stephens, Tom Bray and Lisa Nelson take turns transporting the food to eight different pick up locations; Jil Essinger and other front office staff bring food out to vehicles during curbside pick up; and Bob from Jilbert Dairy is one of many truck drivers who are keeping the food supply chain running!

#MustangProud

Congratulations to Munising High School sophomore Maci Cornish on becoming a FIRST (For Inspiration and Recognition of Science and Technology) Robotics Dean's List Award Finalist! Maci is one of fifteen finalists in the State of Michigan, and will now move on to compete in the FIRST Robotics World Championships!

The students who earn FIRST Dean’s List Award status as a Finalist are great examples of student leaders who have led their teams and communities to increased awareness for FIRST and its mission. These students have also achieved personal technical expertise and accomplishment.

Great work Maci!

Congratulations to the four Munising High School seniors who would have been honored at the Annual Excellence in Education Award Program this evening at NMU had it not been canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Carly Lindquist, Kali Donnelly, Josh Huotari and Ketan Mulye are this year's Excellence in Education scholarship recipients from Munising High School.

Every year, the top five percent of graduating seniors in Marquette County and Alger County receive a $1,500 scholarship to continue their post-secondary education. Even though the award program was canceled, the students will still receive their scholarships.

Also, each scholarship recipient selects a teacher that has been their most influential educator during their educational career. Carly Lindquist and Ketan Mulye selected Mandy Frantti; Kali Donnelly selected Nicole Lasak; and Josh Huotari selected Jim Cotey.

Congratulations students and influential educators!

Gabe went on to win the match in a thrilling double overtime victory, 2-1, to win the District Championship!

Great work Gabe!

For those of you that ordered Sayklly's Easter Eggs this year through the Munising High School Student Council, the eggs will be available for pick up on Thursday, April 9 and Friday, April 10 from noon to 1:00pm each day at the Munising Middle/High School. Please drive up in front of the main entry doors and stay in your vehicle. A school employee will come out and get your name and bring the egg(s) out to you. Unfortunately, there will be no names on the eggs this year, and you may only pick up the eggs you ordered. If you are unable to pick up your eggs prior to Easter, you may pick them up after.

They will still taste great. Happy Easter!

The Munising Middle School student locker contents will be available for pick up on Thursday, April 9 from 11:00am to 1:00pm at the Munising Middle/High School. The contents of each locker have been placed in bags and labeled with the student’s name. Please drive up in front of the main entry doors and stay in your vehicle. A school employee will come out and get the student name and bring you the bag with the locker contents. Some textbooks will be included in the bag, as students will need the books when Munising Public Schools begins its remote learning plan.

Munising High School student locker contents will be available for pick up on Friday, April 10 from 11:00am to 1:00pm as well. We are unable to provide gym locker contents at this time.

Please contact Jil Essinger at 387-2103, extension 2102 if you are unable to get to the school and we will make alternate arrangements for pick up.

As most of you are aware, Governor Whitmer announced this morning that she is suspending face-to-face learning at K-12 schools for the remainder of the school year.

We are in the process of going through the details of the Executive Order, but our students are going to be fine. Seniors will graduate, and the remaining students will move on to their next grade level through a combination of remote learning activities.

The Michigan Department of Education is coming out with their Remote Learning Guidelines early next week, and Munising Public Schools staff is already working on how to conduct the remote learning activities.

As of now, please be patient as we prepare our final plans. If you have an interest in reading through the Executive Order, here is the link:

https://www.michigan.gov/whitmer/0,9309,7-387-90499_90705-524032--,00.html

post_text:
A great quote from Munising Mustang senior Kali Donnelly regarding her internship at Munising Memorial Hospital!
Thank you to Munising Memorial Hospital for providing these great opportunities for our students.
shared_text:
Career Technical Education - Marquette & Alger Counties
April 1 at 3:00 AM ·

Here is a quote from Kali Donnelly from Munising High School who is interning at Munising Memorial Hospital:

"My internship means so much to me, it has allowed me to experience a work environment that I can envision myself in. Giving me a jumpstart on what the job entails. Plus it has given me the ability to be a step above other in the application process. With this in mind, my internship has changed my perspective of the jobs I was certain I wanted to go into. It has opened my eyes to new fields that quite possibly could be a better job than the one I had in mind. I believe if you have the opportunity to get a first hand look at a job you are interested in, you should take it! It allows you to test drive a job before you go and spent thousands of dollars on it. Finally I think it is a tremendous opportunity that everyone should be offered! For me I am going to stay curious and be a sponge to the knowledge I am learning! Thank you to everyone who has given me the privilege to have the internship I currently hold."

Congratulations to the Munising Mustangs boys basketball team and to Mustangs Josh Huotari, Austin Killips, Jason Cornish and Kane Nebel on their Skyline Central Conference awards!

The Mustangs ended up as co-champions with Norway for the Large Schools division of the league. Josh Huotari was a unanimous First Team honoree along with earning a berth on the All-Defensive Team. Austin Killips made the Second Team, while Jason Cornish joined Huotari on the All-Defensive Team. All are seniors.

Freshman Kane Nebel earned an all-league honorable mention nod.

Congratulations as well to Superior Central's Parker Maki who was an honorable mention pick.

Here is the Mining Journal article with photos and complete details on the conference selections.

post_text: Audree Hines, a senior at Munising Middle/High School, has been selected as this week’s Middle/High School Student of the Week. She is the daughter of Carrie and Jamie Kienitz and Ed Hines. Audree is a very determined, hard working student and student-athlete. She is kind hearted and is always willing to help out and lend a hand. Audree plays volleyball and tennis, runs cross country, and plays basketball where she has been a part of three District Championship teams. She also participates in Student Council, Key Club, the Peer-to-Peer program, she does an internship at Munising Memorial Hospital, is the President of HOSA, is a member of the Honor Roll, and spends part of her day in Advanced Child Development working with students at Mather Elementary School. Audree also spends her summers working for Day Camp at APRD. She plans to attend Northern Michigan University in the fall to pursue a degree in medicine. Congratulations to Audree and her parents. Keep up the hard work!

As you are likely aware, on Thursday, March 12, 2020, Governor Gretchen Whitmer announced that in order to slow the spread of Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) in Michigan, she is ordering the closure of all K-12 school buildings, public, private, and boarding, to students starting Monday, March 16, 2020 until Sunday, April 5, 2020. School buildings are scheduled to reopen on Monday, April 6. As of the date of this letter, we do not know if the school year will need to be extended in June.

Attached is a letter that provides guidance for parents/guardian during the closure. Parents/Guardians will also receive a hard copy in the mail.

We appreciate everyone's patience and support during this unprecedented time for our students, schools and country.
text:
As you are likely aware, on Thursday, March 12, 2020, Governor Gretchen Whitmer announced that in order to slow the spread of Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) in Michigan, she is ordering the closure of all K-12 school buildings, public, private, and boarding, to students starting Monday, March 16, 2020 until Sunday, April 5, 2020. School buildings are scheduled to reopen on Monday, April 6. As of the date of this letter, we do not know if the school year will need to be extended in June.

Attached is a letter that provides guidance for parents/guardian during the closure. Parents/Guardians will also receive a hard copy in the mail.

We appreciate everyone's patience and support during this unprecedented time for our students, schools and country.

The MHSAA District Final between the Munising Mustangs and the Negaunee Miners will not be played this Friday due to the MHSAA suspending their postseason tournaments. Here is the statement from the MHSAA:

MHSAA STATEMENT ON CORONAVIRUS AND POSTSEASON TOURNAMENTS

Postseason events sponsored by the Michigan High School Athletic Association have been suspended immediately and indefinitely due to concerns related to COVID-19.

“Based on the events of the last 48 hours and with things changing by the minute, we believe we have no choice but to suspend our winter tournaments immediately,” MHSAA Executive Director Mark Uyl said. “This is a suspension until we have a better handle on the situation. The health and welfare of everyone involved is our number one priority.”
Complete Information and Updates can be found by following this page: MHSAA Coronavirus Updates

The Michigan High School Athletic Association (MHSAA) announced this morning that only a limited number of spectators will be allowed into their postseason tournaments, including the MHSAA Boys Basketball District Final in Negaunee on Friday at 7:00pm.

Each school will be limited to 50 spectators, to include only parents, legal guardians and essential administrators. Munising Public Schools administration is working in conjunction with our boys basketball coaching staff to determine who will attend.

MHSAA Coronavirus updates can be found at the following link:

https://www.mhsaa.com/coronavirus

post_text: Kaelan Mulye, a sophomore student at Munising Middle/High School, has been selected as this week’s Middle/High School Student of the Week. He is the son of Tara and Rick Mulye. Mr. Stephens chose Kaelan and stated, “He is always courteous when you talk with him, he has outstanding work habits and attention to detail. He is inquisitive, and a great role model for other students.” Kaelan is a member of the Cross Country team, Tennis team, Robotics team, Yearbook Committee, Key Club, Drama Club, Quiz Bowl, is on the Honor Roll, and is a mentor for Middle School Robotics. In his free time he enjoys ballet and working at Pictured Rocks Cruises. Congratulations to Kaelan and his parents. Keep up the great work!

post_text: We are pleased to announce that Everette Nettleton has been chosen as the Mather Elementary Student of the Week. Everette is the son of Chris Nettleton and Kora Mills. Everette is an extremely kind and helpful student. He is always ready to help out another student or teacher. He tries his best to tackle assignments and tasks with enthusiasm. His happy and easy-going attitude make up his great character and is an absolute pleasure to be around. Everette is a member of the 4th grade boys’ basketball team and is on the weekly bowling league. In his spare time he enjoys ice skating, downhill skiing, hunting and fishing. Congratulations to Everette and his family!
